We need to be able to extend the available build-able objects in a pre-compiled application to run coupled simulations where a particular object doesn't belong in either application until they are coupled together.

Another use case for this would be to distribute a pre-built binary and header files and dynamically register new objects.

# Design
 - Create a new entry point in the application `void AnimalName__registerObjects(Factory *)`
 - In a Multiapp setting we'll normally pass the parent Factory to the subapp instead of instantiating a separate Factory object. This will have the effect of registering all objects in a single Factory.
 - We'll be able to turn off inheriting the factory through a new parameter in the `Multiapp` block: `inherit_factory`?
 - The same mechanism will be used for the plug-in architecture outside of the Multiapp system.
```
[Problem]
  register_objects = 'OtherAnimal1App OtherAnimal2App'
[]
```

I plan on implementing this tomorrow (2/25) so that @andrsd can make use of it in a large sprint problem. If you have comments or feedback on the design please let me know.

When I tried to remove yak's dependency on legacy UO initialization, I encounter this issue.

I have few stateful material properties for transient simulations whose initial state is at some sort of equilibrium, or in another words, they depend on a normal material property which is evaluated from the primal variables and some other normal material properties at the beginning of the transient. Because of this, these material properties can not be set currently in `Material::initStatefulProperties(unsigned int n_points)`. Normal material properties will simply not be evaluated in the method.

For stateful material properties, `computeProperties()` should not be called at initial or `computeProperties()` should not do the evaluation at initial. But currently there is no such a protection in place.

So I can and have to go back to the old fashion, implement the initialization in `computeProperties()`, where I check if the evaluation is at time zero. This used to work because `FEProblem::initialSetup()` will evaluate all UOs and in turn the `computeProperties()` will be called.

But now only the UOs on initial is evaluated. If there no UO on initial the `computeProperties()` will never be called and leave the stateful material property uninitialized. If there are AuxKernels on initial, `computeProperties()` can still be called, but there is no guarantee AuxKernels on initial exist.

You may wonder why I did not use AuxKernel and let the kernel run both on initial and residual. The reasons are: 1) we used to not have high-order aux variables; 2) we used to not have multiple execute_on. After those two were fixed, I really do not have strong arguments to keep using stateful material properties. My only arguments left are that it will be painful for me to make the change and this is an inherent issue of stateful material properties and can be solved IMO.

I will submit an initial PR for this.
/issues?state=open.title: On initialization of stateful material properties

I'd like to make the element storage and the mathematical operator for RankFourTensor and RankTwoTensor symmetry aware. I.e. a fully isotropic tensor will store only two numbers and have a rotation that is a NOP. Adding two isotropic tensors will give a result that is also an isotropic tensor etc.

For this to work with material properties (which do _not_ support polymorphism), I'm making the element storage in the RankFourTensor and RankTwoTensor classes dynamic, add a field that stores the current symmetry, and expand all operators and members, to properly take the symmetry into account.

If all works well, this change should be completely transparent to the user. I.e. any element of a tensor T can still be accessed through T(i,j,k,l), where for high symmetry tensors the values are computed on the fly. When writing to elements using T(i,j,k,l) = value the symmetry of the tensor is automatically downgraded if necessary.

In the long run I hope this can help convince people to use the TensorMechanics module even if they may work only with isotropic tensors.

Ok - time to finally get this right.

Here's what we're going to do:

1.  Users will throw Exceptions when something goes wrong in their models.
2.  Those Exceptions will be caught _locally_ within the threaded loops (propagating exceptions across threads is ridiculous).
3.  When caught in a thread (in `ThreadedElementLoopBase`) it should call something like `_fe_problem.setException()` or whatever to set a flag that there has been an exception.
4.  Threaded element loop will check that flag and `break` if it's set.
5.  Outside the `ThreadedElementLoop` we will do an MPI "max" or whatever to get the flag across processors (note: We do not care that other processes will have kept running _their_ threaded element loops while the one processor that had an exception is hanging around waiting on them).
6.  If the MPI max comes back showing that a processor had an exception then the MOOSE code itself will throw a _new_ exception (to unwind out of some place a few levels down in `computeResidual()`).
7.  `computeResidual()` will have a try/catch wrapped around it.
8.  When `computeResidual()` catches an exception it will call `SNESSetFunctionDomainError()` (to end the iterations)
9.  Profit??

Once this is finished we should be able to close these (And maybe more):
#2049
#2225
#2269
/issues?state=open.title: Proper Exception Handling

We need to be able to change the MooseApp that is used when you run an executable.  This will allow better testing for MultiApp dominated applications.

I propose two bits:

1.  We add a `--app` option for the command-line to all MOOSE applications.  Then in `AppFactory::createApp()` (which we call in `main()`) we check for that and if it's specified we build _that_ MooseApp and return it.

2.  We add a `[MooseApp]` block to the input file that takes a `type` parameter to specify the MooseApp that should be used to run that input file.  In `AppFactory::createApp()` we quickly parse the input file looking for `[MooseApp]` and if it's specified we build and return that MooseApp as the one that `main()` should be using.

Note:  `createApp()` prototype won't change.  You will still call it in `main()` like:

```
MooseApp * app = AppFactory::createApp("RedbackApp", argc, argv);
```

It's just that the app name that you pass in (in this example `RedbackApp`) will now be the "default" App that can be overridden by either of the above two mechanisms.

Possibly there are two physics forming a coupled system. The transient of one physics is so fast comparing with they other physics, so that at any time it reaches steady state instantaneously, i.e. its time derivative is zero. In this case, if this fast physics is modeled with a MultiApp, it will use the Steady executioner. We then have no choice but the FullSolveMultiApp at least for now. The current implementation in FullSolveMultiApp is not ready for this kinds of simulations. For example, `ex->init()` is called inside `solveStep()`; `auto_advance` is not allowed, and so on. We should have an improved version of it so that it can be used for fast physics along a transient physics. I believe those improvements should be quite strait-forward.

This also creates a related question: if we had to create steps to do a steady solve for the quasi-steady physics, we would not want to use the steps to constrain the time step of the master physics. It seems to me that we should use the FullSolveMultiApp to wrap the fast physics even it is using Transient executioner. I do not know how this will go.

Comments are welcome.

The generalized eigenvalue problem can be expressed as
A*x = k*B*x,
where k is the eigenvalue, x is the solution vector, matrix A and B correspond two sets of kernels.

There are essentially two eigenvalue executioners inside Yak right now: PowerMethodExeutioner and NonlinearEigenExecutioner. As the name suggested, PowerMethodExecutioner uses the inverse power method to find the minimum eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector, and NonlinearEigenExecutioner uses JFNK to solve the eigenvalue problem.

While PowerMethodExeucitioner is simple, in which we just need to make the set of kernels corresponding to B operates on the old solution vector, NonlinearEigenExecutioner is not that simple. NonlinearEigenExecutioner requires a good initial guess on k and x, so that the converged solution is the minimum eigenvalue and its eigenvector. This initial guess is typically obtained by doing few power iterations at the beginning. This poses a difficulty on the implementation with MOOSE, because now the set of kernels for B will operate on old solution vector at the beginning during the free power iterations and operate on the current solution during the nonlinear solve later. We need this NonlinearEigenExecutioner to get the solution faster than PowerMethodExecutioner most of times.

Another option on eigenvalue executioner is using arpack or Slepsc. But power method and nonlinear executioners still have their merit because they runs faster by considering only the fundamental mode (the minimum eigenvalue).

These executioners are frequently affected by MOOSE updates and are hard to maintain by developers other than MOOSE developers. Also having these executioners inside MOOSE will benefit lots of users who may be also interested in solving eigenvalue problems.

Thanks!
/issues?state=open.title: Move eigenvalue executioners from Yak to MOOSE

The way MOOSE handles Dirichlet bcs is to zero the row in the matrix associated with the appropriate degree of freedom, place a one on the diagonal entry, and replace the RHS at that row with the prescribed value.  This has the drawback of the magnitude of the stiffness for that row being predetermined regardless of the magnitude of the row before the change or of the magnitude of the stiffness generally.  This adversely affects the conditioning of the problem, and in some cases the solver does not recover.

It would be helpful if scaling options were available for Dirichlet bcs.  For example, instead of using one on the diagonal, MOOSE could use the sum of the absolute values of the entries on the row and scale the RHS accordingly.  Another idea would be to allow the user to set the diagonal value.
/issues?state=open.title: Scaling for Dirichlet bcs

Constraints, like TiedValueConstraint, work well with small problems and few variables.  However, with larger problems and more variables, they become unworkable.  The reason, at least in part, is due to the fact that every coupling possibility between all dofs associated with elements attached to a slave node and all dofs associated with elements attached to the nearest master node is assumed to be needed.  (See NonlinearSystem::findImplicitGeometricCouplingEntries.)  The memory associated with these constraint equations is requested, and this memory grows quickly, quickly enough to make once moderately sized problems very large.

It would be very helpful if only the coupling equations actually used were part of the preconditioning matrix.  It would also be useful to allow other constraint equation patterns (like a straight penalty approach with only a single slave node and the nodes of the master face).
/issues?state=open.title: Improve Constraint implementation

Ok - it might be time to add vector variables.  Here's how I see this working out

1.  Input Syntax:
```
[ [./velocity](./Variables]
)
    type = Vector
    family = LAGRANGE
    order = FIRST
  [../]

```
That will implicitly create velocity_x, velocity_y and velocity_z depending on the dimension of the problem.

2)  Next up is Kernels.  We need a "VectorKernel".  It's computeQpResidual() function will take an argument of type TypeVector reference (ie computeQpResidual(TypeVector & res) ).  Inside computeQpResidual() it will be the Kerne's job to fill in that TypeVector with the residual for the x, y, z directions.

This Kernel will still have things like _phi, _grad_u... but those will be vectors/matrices as needed.

3)  Coupling

Coupling to vector variables will be handled in two ways:

3a) Using the old coupledValue() style functions you can couple directly to the individual components (like velocity_y).

3b) New coupling functions like coupledVectorValue(), coupledVectorGradient(), etc.


How will all of this be implemented under the hood?  I'm not exactly sure yet.  We could make a VectorMooseVariable class that's responsible for computing the values of these guys... but I'm not sure we need to. Ok - I think I have a handle on how we can solve for different variables on different meshes but solve the whole thing fully coupled!

First it starts with an idea: we are going to make _one_ mesh file that contains the meshes for each variable... and each mesh for each variable will have a different block #.

So, let's say we are going to solve for two variables: u, v on two different meshes of the same 2D, square domain.

The mesh file will actually contain _two_ unjoined meshes laying over the top of one another, covering the exact same domain.  The one for u will be "Block 1" and the one for v will be "Block 2".

Then in the input file we do this:
```
[ [./u](Variables]
)
    ...
    solve_on = 1
    transfer_to = '2'
  [ [./v](../]

)
    ...
    solve_on = 2
    transfer_to = '1'
  [../]

```
This will cause the following:

1.  "u" will be subdomain restricted to block 1, "v" to block 2

2.  Two auxiliary variables will be created:
  - On block 2 an aux variable named "u_transfer"
  - On block 1 an aux variable named "v_transfer"

3.  At the beginning of computeResidual() we will do all of the interpolations from the blocks the variables are solved on to the blocks that they need to be transferred to storing the values in those aux variables.  For now, we'll just use the libMesh MeshFunction stuff, but later we'll figure out better ways to do the interpolation.

4.  Inside MooseVariable::computeElemValues() if the element is not on the subdomain this variable is being solved on, the coefficients for evaluating that variable will come from the auxiliary variable.  But the values will still be stored in the same place (so coupling will work correctly... you'll still just couple to "u")

In this way everything will be transparent to every other part of MOOSE.  Everything should just work.  Coupling, etc won't even have to change.

What do you guys think?
/issues?state=open.title: Fully Coupled on Dissimilar Meshes

We seems to reach an agreement on that the executioners can and should be improved so that they are more developer-friendly.


Below is my original post on the Moose-users regarding to this matter:

*A suggestion on the implementation of executioners*

I am feeling that putting lots of locally used variables into the executioner class is a bad practice. For example, '_converged, _cutback_occurred, _time_old, _prev_dt, _reset_dt ...' in the Transient executioner. Also '_time, _t_step, _dt, _dt_old from the problem' in the Transient executioner do not have to be declared. They look like the 'global' variables shared by the methods of the executioner class. Because the executioner could be fairly complicated, these global variables make hard for developers to understand the implementation of the executioners, which in my opnion is very important for them to add any desired new features. I suggest that somebody takes the responsibility to restructure the executioners. Variables needs to be declared as local as possible.

This seems not very ugent. And it could be a headache. But it will benefit all of us and make possible more developers participate the development of executioners.



Cody's reply:

I like this message and fundamentally you are correct but this
is actually somewhat difficult to do in practice. In some cases these
variables are almost like global variables in that they are shared to
the kernels and other systems in MOOSE and they really need to be this
way. In other cases some of these variables could be made more local
but then that limits our user's ability to customize these
executioners to fit their needs. If you have ideas on ways we can
improve we welcome your suggestions.


My reply back to Cody:

I think events like setting '_time' is significant, they should not be buried into a subroutine. Maybe we can change the name to __time, so we know it is a variable shared by other systems. 

I suggest let just remove all of these variables defined in the class and declare them in the 'execute' method and put everything in 'execute'. Then we try to cut 'execute' and use subroutine arguments for passing info. We may not be able to cut it properly for future extendability at the beginning. But as time goes by, it will grow better.
/issues?state=open.title: Improvement on executioners
